Food Classification using Convolutional Neural Networks¶

Author: Laurice Camille Delos Santos

Executive Summary¶

Automatic and accurate assessment of nutrional intake of food aims to improve the general health and well-being of people. To be able to have an automatic assessment, it is important to fist identify the food categories. In this study, the goal of the researcher is to classify food images using different CNN models. The food image dataset came from the Food-11 dataset, located at the Multimedia Signal Processing Group MMSPG website. Ten classes of food are chosen, namely: bread, dairy, dessert, egg, fried food, meat, pasta/noodles, seafood, soup and vegetables/fruit.

In building the neural network, a baseline CNN model is generated along with pretrained models such as VGG16, ResNet50 and MobileNet. Moreover, activation functions like RELU and ELU are tested in the hidden layers of the different models. RMSprop is used as the optimizer, with 0.001 initial learning rate. Since the study is a multiclassification problem, softmax activation function is used in the output layer. For the model to be generalizable, data augmentation is used. Sparse categorical cross entropy is chosen as the loss function since the targets(classes) are represented by integers. To achieve the highest possible validation accuracy, the best weights are saved and shall be used by the model as far as its considered the best. This behavior is characterized by the ModelCheckpoint library. Fifty epochs are run and 100 steps are used per epoch.

Results showed that the Baseline CNN model, ResNet50 and MobileNet achieved an accuracy greater than the PCC which is equal to 13%. Among all the models, MobileNet generated the highest test accuracy equal to 82% either using RELU or ELU as activation functions. Moreover, Several challenges in the dataset are encountered such as large intraclass variability, multilabel images and large interclass similarity. Multilabel approach, transfer learning and mobile applications should be taken into consideration for further studies.

Introduction¶

Automatic and accurate assessment of nutrional intake of food aims to improve the general health and well-being of people. To be able to have an automatic assessment, it is important to fist identify the food categories. Sometimes, it can be difficult to differentiate certain food item through images since classification can only be based on texture, color and shape. For this study, it would be sufficient enough to recognize the general type of a certain food item, to which dietary value can be estimated, e.g. the amount in calories. It can already provide people with basic information on their daily intake.

Data Description¶

The food image dataset came from Food-11 dataset, located at the Multimedia Signal Processing Group MMSPG website. Originally, there are 11 classes. But due to unbalanced number of samples per class, only 10 classes are chosen in this study. Class are bread, dairy, dessert, egg, fried food, meat, pasta/noodles, seafood, soup and vegetables/fruit. The images are downloaded into a zip file.

Modelling¶

In generating an accurate classification algorithm, several convolutional neural network models are used. These involve the basic CNN model which represent as baseline, and pretrained models such as VGG 16, ResNet50 and MobileNet. Moreover, activation functions like RELU and ELU are tried in the hidden layers of the different models. RMSprop is used as the optimizer, with 0.001 initial learning rate. Since the study is a multiclassification problem, softmax activation function is used in the output layer.

Using RELU Activation Function in the Hidden Layers¶

A. Baseline CNN Model¶

The baseline CNN model consists of 8 RELU layers. For every block, BatchNormalization, MaxPooling and Dropout are done to prevent overfitting and to minimize the number of parameters.

In [8]:
num_classes = 10
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu',
input_shape=(120, 120, 3)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.4))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))#multiclass

from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from keras import optimizers
from keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint

Furthermore, data augmentation is used for the model to be generalizable. Sparse categorical cross entropy is chosen as the loss function since the targets(classes) are represented by integers. To achieve the highest possible validation accuracy, the best weights are saved and shall be used by the model as far as its considered the best. This behavior is characterized by the ModelCheckpoint library. 50 epochs are run and 100 steps are used per epoch.

In [12]:
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
rescale=1./255,
rotation_range=40,
width_shift_range=0.2,
height_shift_range=0.2,
shear_range=0.2,
zoom_range=0.2,
horizontal_flip=True)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_dir,
    target_size=(120, 120),
    batch_size=64,
    class_mode='sparse')

test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    target_size=(120, 120),
    batch_size=64,
    class_mode='sparse')

model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
optimizer=keras.optimizers.RMSprop(0.001),
metrics=['acc']) 

filepath="weights-improvement-{epoch:02d}-{val_acc:.2f}.hdf5" #Save the Improve model here
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath, monitor='val_acc', verbose=1, save_best_only=True, mode='max')
callbacks_list = [checkpoint]

history = model.fit_generator(
    train_generator,
    steps_per_epoch=100,
    epochs=50,
    validation_data=test_generator,
    validation_steps=50,
    callbacks=callbacks_list, 
    verbose=0)

Pretrained Models¶

In training small scale image datasets, it is best to use a pretrained network. Since pretrained networks are trained in a large dataset, the spatial hierarchy of the features these have learned can represent as a generic model of the visual world. In this study, all the pretrained models are trained on ImageNet where classes are mostly animals and everyday objects.

B. VGG16¶

Visual Geometry Group (VGG) 16 is a 16-layer convolutional neural network designed for large-scale image recognition.

In [14]:

C. ResNet50¶

ResNet50 is a 50-layer residual network in which we create a deeper network by having skip connections to increase accuracy, without experiencing vanishing gradient problem.

In [18]:
from keras.applications import resnet50, mobilenet

Furthermore, data augmentation is used for the model to be generalizable. Sparse categorical cross entropy is chosen as the loss function since the targets(classes) are represented by integers. To achieve the highest possible validation accuracy, the best weights are saved and shall be used by the model as far as its considered the best. This behavior is characterized by the ModelCheckpoint library. 50 epochs are run and 100 steps are used per epoch.

MobileNet has a computationally efficient CNN architecture designed specifically for mobile devices with very limited computing power since it has less number of parameters.

Using ELU Activation Function in the Hidden Layers¶

All the methods and parameters are similar to what are discussed above. The only difference here is that ELU is used as the activation function in the hidden layers of the Baseline CNN Model, VGG 16, ResNet50 and MobileNet.

A. Baseline CNN Model¶

The baseline CNN model consists of 8 RELU layers. For every block, BatchNormalization, MaxPooling and Dropout are done to prevent overfitting and to minimize the number of parameters.

In [12]:
num_classes = 10
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='elu',
input_shape=(120, 120, 3)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.4))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='elu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

model.add(Flatten())

Pretrained Models¶

In training small scale image datasets, it is best to use a pretrained network. Since pretrained networks are trained in a large dataset, the spatial hierarchy of the features these have learned can represent as a generic model of the visual world. In this study, all the pretrained models are trained on ImageNet where classes are mostly animals and everyday objects.

B. VGG 16¶

Visual Geometry Group (VGG) 16 is a 16-layer convolutional neural network designed for large-scale image recognition.

In [19]:
from keras.applications import VGG16,VGG19

conv_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet',
                  include_top=False,
                  input_shape=(120, 120, 3))
In [20]:

Furthermore, data augmentation is used for the model to be generalizable. Sparse categorical cross entropy is chosen as the loss function since the targets(classes) are represented by integers. To achieve the highest possible validation accuracy, the best weights are saved and shall be used by the model as far as its considered the best. This behavior is characterized by the ModelCheckpoint library. 50 epochs are run and 100 steps are used per epoch.

Challenges in the Dataset¶

In [48]:
def food(img,folder):
    plt.imshow(resize(imread('food/train/' + folder + '/'+ img),(200,200)))
    plt.xlabel(folder)

1.) Large intraclass variability – In this case, both the glass of milk and the blocks of cheese are under the Dairy class even though these are not visually similar.

In [49]:
food('1_14.jpg','dairy')
In [50]:
food('1_13.jpg','dairy')

2.) There are multilabel images, since the classes are too general. In the image below, fruits like kiwi and strawberries can be recognized, while the waffle itself and the ice cream can be considered as bread and dairy, respectively. But in the dataset, this image is only recognized as dessert.

In [51]:
food('2_788.jpg','dessert')

3.) Large interclass similarity - Notice how similar the omelette is with respect to the toasted bread.

In [52]:
food('3_280.jpg','egg')
In [53]:
food('0_949.jpg','bread')

Recommendations¶

Multilabel approach can be done to recognize images that contain several food classes. Apparently, scikitlearn has a library called  scikit-multilearn in which several methods of multilabel classification can be easily implemented such as Problem Transformation and Adaptive Algorithm. Also, implementing transfer learning can be done to classify different sets of food images which are not limited to the ten classes discussed. Finally using the MobileNet model, running this classification algorithm as an application on mobile devices would be efficient since the number of parameters and the computing power were reduced without compromising on accuracy.
